2. Docker Fundamentals

Docker packages applications with dependencies into isolated containers.

Core Concepts

Image → Immutable blueprint
Container → Running instance
Registry → Image storage system
Docker Engine → Runtime

3. Basic Docker Commands

docker version
docker help
docker search nginx  # looks for nginx images from the terminal 
docker pull nginx    
docker images

docker ps   # shows the active containers
docker ps -a   # shows all the containers: running, stopped, exited...

Run Containers

docker run nginx
docker run -it ubuntu # we create the container and enter to it.
docker run -itd ubuntu # with d, the container is created but we do not enter to it. 

Flags
-i → interactive
-t → terminal
-d → detached mode

4. Container Lifecycle

Created → Running → Paused → Stopped → Removed

Management

docker start container     # starts a stopped container
docker stop container      # stops a container gracefully (allows cleanup/shutdown)
docker restart container   # restarts a container (stop + start)
docker pause container     # suspends all processes inside the container
docker unpause container   # resumes a paused container
docker kill container      # forcefully stops a container immediately (SIGKILL)
docker rm container        # removes a container from the system (must be stopped first)
docker rmi image          # removes a Docker image from the local system (must not be used by running containers)

Exec (Production Safe)

docker exec -it container bash   # to exec into a running container using bash sell.
docker exec -it container sh

✔ Safe for debugging
✔ Does NOT attach to main process

5. Debugging Containers

docker logs container        # shows the logs/output of a container
docker logs -f container     # follows (streams) logs in real time
docker inspect container     # shows detailed low-level info about a container (JSON format)
docker stats                 # displays real-time CPU, memory, and network usage of containers
docker top container        # shows running processes inside a container

Key Insight

docker logs = application debugging
docker exec = runtime inspection
docker inspect = metadata + network + mounts

6. Docker Images & Dockerfile (Production Standard)

Build & Manage Images

docker build -t app:1.0 .          # builds a Docker image from the current directory and tags it as app:1.0
docker tag app:1.0 repo/app:v1     # creates a new tag for an existing image (used for versioning or pushing to registries). target: repo/app:v1
docker push repo/app:v1           # uploads the image to a remote Docker registry (e.g., Docker Hub)
docker pull nginx                 # downloads the nginx image from a remote registry
docker history nginx              # shows the layered history of how an image was built
Docker file:

WORKDIR /app                     # sets the working directory inside the container

COPY requirements.txt .         # copies only requirements.txt into the container
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt   # installs Python dependencies without caching

COPY . .                        # copies the rest of the application code into the container

CMD ["python", "app.py"]        # default command that runs when the container starts



SRE Rule

SRE Rule

🚫 Never use docker commit in production   # avoid manual, non-reproducible container changes
✔ Always use CI/CD pipelines              # ensure builds are automated, versioned, and reproducible

7. Docker Networking

Network Types

bridge (default)  # default isolated network; containers get private IPs and communicate via virtual bridge
host              # container uses the host machine’s network directly (no isolation)
none              # disables all networking for the container (completely isolated)

Commands

docker network ls                  # lists all Docker networks on the host
docker network inspect bridge      # shows detailed configuration of the default bridge network (JSON output)
docker network create mynetwork    # creates a new user-defined bridge network called "mynetwork"

Port Mapping

docker run -p 8080:80 nginx   # maps host port 8080 → container port 80 (nginx becomes accessible via localhost:8080)

So when you open:

http://localhost:8080

👉 you are actually hitting nginx inside the container on port 80.

8. Docker Storage & Persistence

Volumes

docker volume create data_volume        # creates a named persistent volume managed by Docker
docker volume ls                        # lists all Docker volumes on the system
docker volume inspect data_volume       # shows detailed metadata about a specific volume

Run with Volume (Persistence)
docker run -v data_volume:/var/lib/mysql mysql

👉 Mounts a Docker-managed volume into the container

🧠 Meaning:
data_volume → persistent storage managed by Docker
/var/lib/mysql → where MySQL stores its data inside the container

👉 Result: data survives container deletion. It is used in prod

Bind Mount (Host Path)

docker run -v /host/data:/container/data nginx

🧠 Meaning:

/host/data → real folder on your Mac/Linux
/container/data → folder inside container

👉 This directly links host filesystem ↔ container

📦 Volumes

“Docker-managed persistent disk”

🧷 Bind mounts

“Shared folder between host and container”


SRE Insight


Volumes persist even if containers are deleted.   # data is stored independently of container lifecycle

Used for:

Databases        # persistent storage for structured data (e.g., PostgreSQL, MySQL)
Logs             # durable log storage for debugging and auditing
Stateful systems  # any workload that must keep state across restarts (e.g., queues, caches)


9. Resource Management

docker run --cpus=1 nginx        # limits the container to use at most 1 CPU core
docker run --memory=512m nginx   # limits the container to 512 MB of RAM

Why it matters

Prevents:

| Resource | Risk without limits      |
| -------- | ------------------------ |
| CPU      | latency spikes, slowdown |
| Memory   | crashes (OOMKilled)      |
| Disk/IO  | system-wide lag          |



